    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras are positioned for a high-floor offensive performance today, anchored by **Christian Yelich** (71.15) and **Trea Turner** (70.10). **Christian Yelich** earns our top spot thanks to a favorable matchup against Littell, where a dynamic platoon advantage (+13%) outweighs the modest resistance of an elite catcher. Meanwhile, **Trea Turner** remains an essential start despite facing a formidable arm in Gallen; his spot at the top of the order and elite sprint speed potential make him a must-play to secure stolen bases, even with a slight negative adjustment for the platoon split. **Caleb Durbin** (69.85) is arguably our most exciting play, benefiting from an 85% stolen-base opportunity rate and a crucial +10% wind boost, which elevates his profile significantly against Pallante.\n\nWe continue to prioritize speed and situational alignment, leading to the difficult decision to bench **Victor Scott II** (59.85). While **Victor Scott II** offers the stolen base upside we crave, his assignment to the nine-hole forces a -8% penalty, keeping him just behind **Kazuma Okamoto** (59.06) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (62.10) in our efficiency-weighted model. **Yordan Alvarez** (58.57) presents the highest risk of the day; while his xwOBA remains elite, he is suppressed by a difficult matchup against Gilbert (2.86 xERA) and negative park factors. We are rolling with him regardless due to his high-ceiling profile, but he is a candidate for early-inning frustration. \n\nOwners should monitor **Logan O'Hoppe** (56.62) and **Dillon Dingler** (48.00) closely, as their scores are heavily dependent on dynamic platoon shifts. **Junior Caminero** (62.72) faces a stiff challenge in the form of a neutral-to-negative park adjustment, but his position in the heart of the order and favorable matchup against Schlittler keep him firmly in the \"Strong\" start tier. We are avoiding exposure to **Hyeseong Kim** (42.61) today, as the matchup against deGrom presents an extreme efficiency floor that we cannot afford given our tight game-cap strategy.",
